    "preview": {
      "__component": "lesson-plan.lesson-preview",
      "SectionTitle": "Lesson Preview",
      "QuickPrep": "1. Check out lesson multimedia above\n2. Look over <AnchorLink href=\"#teaching_materials\"> Teaching Materials <\/AnchorLink>\n3. Read our easy <AnchorLink href=\"#procedure\"> Procedure <\/AnchorLink>\n4. Teach it and <AnchorLink href=\"#feedback\"> let us know what you think! <\/AnchorLink>\n",
      "Multimedia": [
        {
          "order": 1,
          "type": "video",
          "title": "How our eyes and brains interact to determine what we like and dislike",
          "description": "This video explores how things we see (visual stimuli) affect emotional states and interact with our memories and higher order thinking (cognition) to produce preferences and behavior. This basic framework is adapted from human and animal behavior research. We use this framework throughout the middle school-targeted lesson below. In the lesson, students perform an experiment to understand their own preferences and dive into research on fish, exploring how sensitivity to different frequencies of light affects mate preferences. We dive into this topic in detail in our second video supporting this lesson.",
          "lessonRelevance": "A fascinating dive into how animals and humans experience the world. Intuitive examples lay out a framework for understanding how visual perception, cognition, and emotion interact to determine our preferences.",
